Moreland collaborated with Leighton Smith on the Wingman project, which was conceived about a year ago during a conversation about brain drain. The project is intentionally community-driven — not by an employer — to help transplants break out of the bubble of their workplace to see what else is here.

"For people who come here for work, we don't do a good enough job getting them involved in our game of double Dutch," Smith said of the jump rope game that can be hard to get started but easier once you do. "Our culture is very friendly — we're Iowa nice — but we don't employ it in effective way, particularly for minority communities."

status_message: The mechanism used to silence Warren is known as Rule 19, an arcane and seldom invoked provision in the Rules of the Senate. The rule states that senators may not "directly or indirectly, by any form of words impute to another Senator or to other Senators any conduct or motive unworthy or unbecoming a Senator." What does it mean for one senator to "impugn" or "impute" another? That's a matter of perspective, but one thing's for sure: the circumstances surrounding Rule 19's creation were quite different from Tuesday's exchange on the Senate floor.
link_name: The silencing of Elizabeth Warren and an old Senate rule prompted by a fistfight | The Gazette

status_message: Iowa is not among the 15 states that prohibit drivers' use of hand-held phones. The past three years have been an unmitigated success for the Republican Party of Iowa under Jeff Kaufmann's stewardship.

No one could have blamed Kaufmann, nor would it have surprised anyone, had he chosen to step aside after a prosperous run as state party chairman and let someone else deal with the many challenges of leading a state political party structure.

But Kaufmann chose to stick around and help Iowa Republicans build on their recent successes, and on Saturday was re-elected to a two-year term as state party chairman.
link_name: Kaufmann hopes to help Iowa GOP sustain success | The Gazette

status_message: "No actor was more perfectly named than John Hurt. It's not as if the people he played were always in pain (though more often than not, they were). Yet he was graced with a seductively layered and tricky personality — you sensed that his characters were sly, furtive, and complicated because Hurt was all those things as well. And the deepest layer was the hint of torment he carried around with him. It was like the speck of sand around which a pearl forms."
link_name: A tribute to the late John Hurt: a playful master who made his inner hurt ours | The Gazette

"For a long time I thought I couldn't be the writer I wanted to be because I lived in Iowa," she said. Eventually, she realized that her home state, which she describes as a "melting pot" of people and ideas, offered her plenty of opportunity for observation of human behavior.

Cedar Rapids used federal money to purchase more than 1,000 properties through the city's voluntary property acquisition program after the 2008 flood. While some houses or businesses have seen revival, others sit idle, in limbo between past and future.

"I really want us to see what we can do to spur some interest in that area in the next couple years. status_message:
Editor's note: The Gazette agrees with those questioning the prominence given to the photo appearing on Facebook showing Cedar Rapids police officer Lucas Jones playing dodgeball.
The photo should not have been selected as the photo of the day. Because of the timing of the post at 11:30 p.m., very few were involved in its selection. The process of selecting photos for this feature will be changed going forward.
With regards to the image remaining on this post, Facebook does not allow the editing of images after publication of a post. This left us with two options, to delete the post entirely, or provide context as we have in this case. Because of the comments on this post, we felt that removing the post entirely would be less transparent.
Since Officer Jones shot Jerime Mitchell on Nov. 1, The Gazette has extensively covered the case. We are continuing to push for additional records to be released through administrative and legal channels.
The Gazette chose to cover the dodgeball event as a longstanding fundraiser with interaction between the CRPD and area students. We were unaware Jones would be in attendance.
We will, however, continue to cover Jones, a member of the Cedar Rapids Police Department, as news merits. 
- Zack Kucharski, Executive Editor

The New Bohemian Innovation Collaborative (NewBoCo) has expanded its Iowa Startup Accelerator from a single fall session to three sessions each year.

An ancient quarter-mile-long display of sacred public art has been memorialized in an image the size of a quarter.

That took some doing, said Richard Masters, an Iowa native who designed the image on the soon-to-be released Effigy Mounds National Monument quarter.

"It was a real challenge to depict some of the mounds with a sense of the scale of their natural setting with the sky and distant trees," said Masters, who has designed many commemorative coins and medals, from in his New York City studio.

In addition to coaching Coe's women's tennis team, Kris Tiedt is also on the wellness committee at Coe College, leads strength and conditioning sessions with Coe's tennis, soccer and golf teams, teaches student fitness classes, parents an 8-year-old at home and is training for an Ironman triathlon this summer.

So how does she do it? Overall wellness, she said.

"Most people think only of physical fitness when they think of wellness — or the proverbial six pack," she said. But when she says wellness, she means six things: physical, intellectual, social, spiritual, emotional and occupational well-being.

The Board of Regents is expected this month to tweak its meeting schedule again, reducing the total number of meetings earlier approved for 2017 and giving board members more time to consider agenda items.

The expected amendment would reduce the total number of board meetings that regents had approved for 2017. But it would make them two-day affairs — keeping with current practice — instead of collapsing most into a single day, with committee meetings held on other dates.

status_message:
The floods of 2008 claimed his home, but still Ron Coppess wanted to come back. He built a new home on a higher lot and has lived there ever since.

"I grew up here," he said. "It was just a good place to leave. Peaceful. Quiet."

Now, floodwaters are threatening the tiny, southeast Cedar Rapids neighborhood again. But like other areas throughout the city, citizens flocked to the neighborhood on Sunday to fill sandbags and try to help the residents there withstand the rising Cedar River. About 50 people were on hand at the Cedar Valley Park Sunday afternoon, filling sandbags, loading them into trucks and delivering them to residents.
link_name: Cedar Valley-Rompot neighbors prepare for flooding | The Gazette

Higher education leaders across Iowa — including those with the Board of Regents and its public universities — have been vocal about their desire to improve in national rankings, namely U.S. News & World Report's annual list of top colleges and universities.

But University of Iowa didn't budge from its spot at No. 82 among national universities on the 2017 U.S. News rankings made public Tuesday. And Iowa State University slipped from No. 108 last year to No. 111 in the new rankings.

However, in positive news, the agricultural and biosystems engineering programs at Iowa State have ascended to number 1 in the rankings in this category.

status_message:
Everywhere you look at the restoration project at 1142 E. Court St. in Iowa City, your gaze falls into beauty. And onto Grant Wood's legacy.

"As I made it my house, I wanted to keep Grant Wood's essence," said Hayes, 77, a partner with the Hayes Lorenzen law firm in Iowa City. "He did so many things here — very, very important artistic things. In fact, he said through his sister, Nan, and she said to me, that Grant Wood always considered his restoration of 1142 one of his highest artistic achievements. He did that much here. ... But I wanted to get back to the original footprint."

Read more, and watch a video on the project, at the link below.

#history #art #restoration #iowa State Historical Society of Iowa, Iowa History Journal
link_name: The house that Grant Wood rebuilt | The Gazette

status_message:
Ready to recognize local excellence in business?

The site is now open for Business 380 Excellence Awards at http://www.thegazette.com/businessawards2016. Nominate your company or one you work with.

The nomination process will continue through 5 p.m., April 29

Once again, The Gazette Business 380 will be recognizing companies and organizations in the following categories:

·  Finance — banks, credit unions
·  Health care — hospitals, research institutions, health exchanges, universities
·  Commercial real estate & development — construction, development, big sales
·  Not-for-profits & associations — service organizations, charities (hospitals will not be considered in this category)
·  Technology — new product lines, opening new markets
·   Manufacturing — new product lines, opening new markets
·   Civic Partner – Demonstrates a proactive, engaged approach in serving the community by which the company and its employees exists.
·   Corporate Culture Award – Achievement in the creation and integration of company values, demonstrated throughout the organization.
·  Innovation - New product or new business systems.
·  Education - Higher education or companies who supply educational products.
·  Business 380 Excellence Award of 2016 — will be selected by the panel from the above category submissions

COMING THIS SUNDAY: A new era for the University of Iowa starts Monday when businessman J. Bruce Harreld begins his tenure as the institution's 21st president. But even before taking office, Harreld has endured faculty, staff, and student criticism on points of his academic administrative experience – or lack thereof – resume concerns, and the search process that led to his hire.

On Sunday, hear from Harreld himself following a sit-down interview with The Gazette.

Other non-traditional candidates, like University of Colorado system President Bruce Benson, also weigh in on what it takes to disprove the doubters.

status_message:
Aquatics therapy helps those with certain disabilities improve strength, mobility and function. The individual therapy sessions take place in the pool over an 8- to 10-week period, helping about 15 children each session.

Therapists use the properties of water — buoyancy, resistance, and weight reduction — to work with the children on tasks and activities that might not be possible on land.
link_name: Pools of Healing: Therapy for disabled kids gets boost from aquatics - TheGazette

status_message:
On this day in history: 

On December 11, 1994, the Gazette reported with the frontpage headline "What Next for U of I" the departure of University of Iowa president Hunter R. Rawlings III, who was then announced as Cornell University's 10th president. University of Iowa's future president David Skorton would later leave the University of Iowa to succeed Rawlings. In between Rawlings and Skorton, Mary Sue Coleman served as president before leaving for the University of Michigan in 2002. 

This photo shows Rawlings photographed by a Gazette staff photographer during his tenure at Iowa. 

#uiowa #tbt #thisdayinhistory #iowa #cornell

Call for submissions!

Earlier this year, the Iowa Racing and Gaming Commission denied Cedar Rapids' bid to license the Cedar Crossing casino. 
Backers say the issue is not dead. Others already have been brainstorming other uses for the nearly eight acres of vacant city-owned land between A Avenue NW and Second Avenue SW, and First and Third streets SW along the Cedar River.
Where some saw slots, others see a new city park, an extreme sports complex or a farm museum. What do you think? 

The Gazette Insight team is collecting community ideas until 5 p.m. on Monday, Aug. 11. 

Send your thoughts to editorial@thegazette.com, leave a message (including name and contact information) at (319) 398-8484 or mail to Letters, The Gazette, 501 2nd Ave SE, Cedar Rapids, IA 52401.

status_message: To deal with animal attacks, some communities have turned to breed-specific legislation, which make it illegal for a person to own a particular breed of dog, such as a pit bull, within city limits. But local animal control officials say that type of law — which singles out one breed of animal — doesn't reduce dog bites, attacks and incidents because dogs of all breeds can express aggression if they aren't trained properly. And more Iowa communities are leaning away from breed-specific bans. Do you agree with that trend? Read more: http://thegaz.us/b7

status_message:
Changes at the pumps beginning this week will likely force motorists to decide between fueling their vehicles with an ethanol blend or paying more. In response to the Federal Renewable Fuels Standard, a regulation that requires more ethanol be mixed with gasoline, refineries will start shipping a sub-octane fuel – 83 or 84 octane, down from 87 octane – through the pipelines to the Midwest. The change to sub-octane will force Iowa gas stations to either blend with ethanol or blend with premium gasoline to reach the minimum 87 octane fuel legal for retail in Iowa. The 87 octane non-ethanol fuel could cost 52 cents per gallon more than the 10 percent ethanol blend.
What do you think? Read more: http://thegaz.us/9e

Delivered 50 years ago on Wednesday, King's image of his dream for a better America still inspires the United States. The speech was delivered to more than 250,000 people who came to Washington, D.C., to march for civil rights at a time when it was still illegal for blacks and whites to marry in many states, and just months after protesters in Alabama were set upon with police dogs and fire hoses.

The U.S. government may be considering military action in response to chemical strikes near Damascus. But a generation ago, America's military and intelligence communities knew about and did nothing to stop a series of nerve gas attacks far more devastating than anything Syria has seen, Foreign Policy has learned.

In 1988, during the waning days of Iraq's war with Iran, the United States learned through satellite imagery that Iran was about to gain a major strategic advantage by exploiting a hole in Iraqi defenses. U.S. intelligence officials conveyed the location of the Iranian troops to Iraq, fully aware that Saddam Hussein's military would attack with chemical weapons, including sarin, a lethal nerve agent.

City leaders say golf courses, like pools, libraries and recreation centers, deserve public support. But with only 1 in 10 Americans playing golf and cities cutting other services, some citizens wonder if municipal courses should be handed over to private contractors.

status_message:
On Thursday, June 12, 2008, the Cedar River rose well beyond its all-time historic flood crest, and was still rising at day's end, en route to a record crest of 31.12 feet Friday morning. It became the most catastrophic flood disaster in Iowa history.

A total of 364 photos were entered into NICA, The Gazette's photo archive database, on June 12. 54 of those photos came from Little Sioux, Iowa, where one of the deadliest tornadoes in Iowa history had killed four Boy Scouts and injured dozens of other people the previous day. 18 photos were from the NCAA championship track meet. 14 others were random photos, mostly features. The other 278 photos entered into NICA from that day came from the flood. Here's just one of those memorable images.

We can't forget. We'll never forget.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
Five years ago today ICE agents raided Agriprocessors, a meat-packing plant in Postville. It was then the largest raid in U.S. history. Community members say life may never be back to "normal," but five years later storefronts are filling up, the school population is on the rise and the new faces in town reflect the ever-changing, diverse population that is Postville.

Read more: http://smgs.us/3ise
View timeline: http://smgs.us/3isf

Photo by Liz Martin/The Gazette.
link_name: Timeline Photos

status_message:
Rosa Zamora and her family were separated five years ago when her husband was deported back to Guatemala after Agriprocessors, the meat-packing plant they both worked in Postville, was raided by ICE agents. 
The community lost at least 389 residents from Mexico and Guatemala and a large percentage of the Jewish residents because of that raid, but the town is slowly starting to rebound.

Read more: http://smgs.us/3ise
View timeline: http://smgs.us/3isf

Photo by Kaitlyn Bernauer/The Gazette.

A picturesque photo of a kayaker on the Turkey River snapped by Jessica Rilling of Cedar Rapids will grace the cover of the 2013 Iowa Travel Guide, to be distributed this spring.

Rilling's photo – among more than 600 submissions to the Iowa Tourism Office – was honored Monday as the winning entry in a special state contest by Gov. Terry Branstad and Lt. Gov. Kim Reynolds.

status_message:
Looking for Union Station memories
Do you or a family member recall Cedar Rapids' Union Station and its neighbors? Did you or they ride the tails from downtown?
In preparation for the National Railway Historical Society's national convention in Cedar Rapids June 17-25, we're (the Gazette? SourceMedia?) taking a look at the railroads' role in the development of the Cedar Rapids-Iowa City area and Eastern Iowa.
We'd like to hear from local residents old enough to recall traveling by rail to and from Eastern Iowa, who worked for the railroads here, or who recall when Cedar Rapids' Union Station was still in business. We're especially interested if you have old photos or other local souvenirs of the railroad era.
If you or someone in your family are would like to participate, we'd like to hear from you. Call Steve Gravelle at (319)398-5819, or contact him by email at steve.gravelle@sourcemedia.net.

WASHINGTON (AP) — President Barack Obama says Osama bin Laden, the glowering mastermind behind the Sept. 11, 2001, terror attacks that killed thousands of Americans, was killed in an operation led by the United States.

A small team of Americans carried out the attack and took custody of bin Laden's remains, the president said Sunday in a dramatic late-night statement at the White House.

Volleyball blogger wanted: GazetteOnline and IowaPrepSports.com are looking for someone – preferably a player or coach -- who would be willing to blog or tweet for us during the State High School Volleyball Tournament in Cedar Rapids next Wednesday-Saturday, Nov. 11-14.

Don't worry, we (probably) don't want you blogging during your matches. But we WOULD like consistent feeds before and after your matches on everything from the competition to the arena to the atmosphere inside and outside the building.

Sound like something you'd be interested in doing? Contact Nick Pugliese, Manager of Sports Content, at (319) 368-8821 or nick.pugliese@gazcomm.com, or sportswriter Jeff Linder at (319) 368-8857 or jeff.linder@gazcomm.com

Some changes to The Gazette : Starting March 10th, The Gazette will transition to a 3 section paper Monday - Saturday. 
Section A = Local News, Editorial / Opinion Page, National News. 
Section B = Sports, Obituaries, Business. 
Section C = Features/Accent, Comics, Puzzles, Classifieds.
